SIMPLE: else
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Else
<hw>Else</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a. & pron.</pos> <ety>[OE. & AS.
<ets>elles</ets> otherwise, gen. sing. of an adj. signifying
<ets>other</ets>; akin to OHG. <ets>elles</ets> otherwise, OSw.
<ets>⟦aum⟧ljes</ets>, Sw. <ets>eljest</ets>, Goth. <ets>aljis</ets>,
adj., other, L. <ets>alius</ets>, Gr. <?/. Cf. <er>Alias</er>,
<er>Alien</er>.]</ety> <def>Other; one or something beside; <as>as, Who
<ex>else</ex> is coming? What <ex>else</ex> shall I give? Do you expect
anything <ex>else</ex>?</as></def> ⟦ldquo⟧Bastards and
<xex>else</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ This word always follows its noun. It is usual to give
the possessive form to <xex>else</xex> rather than to the substantive;
as, somebody <xex>else's</xex>; no one <xex>else's</xex>. ⟦ldquo⟧A boy
who is fond of somebody <xex>else's</xex> pencil case.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>G.
Eliot.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧A suit of clothes like everybody
<xex>else's</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Thackeray.</au></rj> </note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Else</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Else
<hw>Else</hw>, <pos>adv. & conj.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Besides; except
that mentioned; in addition; <as>as, nowhere <ex>else</ex>; no one
<ex>else</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Otherwise; in the other, or the contrary, case; if
the facts were different.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For thou desirest not sacrifice; <qex>else</qex> would I give
it.</q> <rj><qau>Ps. li. 16.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ After ⟦lsquo⟧or', <xex>else</xex> is sometimes used
expletively, as simply noting an alternative. ⟦ldquo⟧Will you give
thanks, . . . or <xex>else</xex> shall I?⟦rdquo⟧</note>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Elsewhere</ent>⟦br⟧
